ople want to play and what is fun, from login to logout, to play. Somewhere around Luclin the EQ devs totally lost these skills.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think it bears mentioning that shortly after Luclin, the vast majority of the original developers (Bard McQuaid, Jeff Buttler, etc.) left Sony and formed their own company, <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.sigilgames.com">Sigil Games</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. Though they made some unpopular design decisions, they stuck to their guns and made some of the most importantly addictive and realistically immersive concepts for implementation in EverQuest. EQ's success, on the whole, is largely attributed by its lack of same-scale competition and marketting (Asheron's Call was no match and Dark Age of Camelot arrived far too late on the scene to compete). Now that competition is emerging over the horizon, SOE has to make the game appeal to the common denominator of its active subscriber base - which means lowering the level of difficulty and reducing the degree of time-sink that the game has. It's an unfortunate choice that will benefit only those who stick with EverQuest as the months continue to turn into years, but the open competition is sure to inspire the folks at Sigil Games to, hopefully, come out with a product that will rival World of Warcraft.<br>
<br>
Kaelon <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.kaelon.com/images/kaesiggy2.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
